training_organizations.name: Texas DFPS Professional Development (Training Academy)
training_organizations.description: The Texas Department of Family and Protective Services runs a centralized training academy for all new CPS caseworkers and investigators. Trainees undergo classroom instruction on Texas laws, IMPACT system use, and DFPS policies, along with on-the-job training with a mentor. Specialized tracks exist for Investigations vs. Conservatorship caseworkers. This ensures a baseline of practice knowledge before staff are assigned cases. DFPS also provides ongoing training, and with recent reforms, places emphasis on topics like trauma-informed care and normalcy for foster youth.

training_organizations.name: Texas University Partnerships (Title IV-E Programs)
training_organizations.description: Texas collaborates with multiple universities (such as University of Texas at Austin, Texas State, University of Houston, etc.) through Title IV-E education programs. These partnerships provide stipends and specialized training to social work students who commit to work for CPS, creating a pipeline of well-prepared graduates. They also involve faculty in developing curriculum and research for DFPS. In addition, DFPS uses universities to deliver certain trainings and evaluations; for example, the University of Texas – Arlington helps run the CPS Leadership Academy. These partnerships bolster workforce quality and retention.

training_organizations.name: Community-Based Care Lead Agencies (SSCCs)
training_organizations.description: Texas is transitioning to a Community-Based Care model, wherein DFPS contracts regional Single Source Continuum Contractors (SSCCs) to manage foster care and services:contentReference[oaicite:43]{index=43}:contentReference[oaicite:44]{index=44}. Notable examples include ACH Child & Family Services (Our Community Our Kids) in Region 3B (Fort Worth area), 2INgage (a partnership of Texas Family Initiative & New Horizons) in Region 2 (Northwest TX), and Saint Francis Ministries in Region 1 (Texas Panhandle). These nonprofits coordinate foster home recruitment, case management, and reunification/adoption services for children in their regions, under DFPS oversight and measured by performance outcomes.

training_organizations.name: ACH Child & Family Services (OCOK)
training_organizations.description: A Fort Worth-based nonprofit that serves as the SSCC for DFPS Region 3B. Branded as “Our Community Our Kids,” ACH has full responsibility for children in foster care in that area – finding and licensing foster homes, placing children, managing their cases, and arranging services – all aimed at improving stability and achieving permanency. ACH/OCOK works under a performance-based contract and was one of the first pilots of Community-Based Care in Texas:contentReference[oaicite:45]{index=45}.

training_organizations.name: 2INgage
training_organizations.description: The SSCC for DFPS Region 2, covering northwest Texas. 2INgage is a partnership between two nonprofits (Texas Family Initiative and New Horizons) that collectively manage foster care and family services in their region. They handle everything from foster parent recruitment to case management for children removed by DFPS, striving for better outcomes through community-driven care. 2INgage’s contract includes meeting targets for safety, placement stability, and permanency for the children it serves:contentReference[oaicite:46]{index=46}.

training_organizations.name: Saint Francis Ministries (Texas)
training_organizations.description: A faith-based nonprofit that DFPS selected as the SSCC for Region 1 (the Panhandle area):contentReference[oaicite:47]{index=47}. Saint Francis Ministries is responsible for providing the full continuum of foster care services in that region, including placement in foster homes or facilities, oversight of case plans, and support services to families aiming to reunify. They progressed to "Stage II" which means they assumed legal case management from DFPS for children in care, making them the lead entity for day-to-day decisions while DFPS monitors performance.

training_organizations.name: Texas CASA
training_organizations.description: A statewide nonprofit association that supports the 72 local CASA programs in Texas. Texas CASA provides training curriculum, advocacy at the state legislature, and organizational development for CASA offices. CASA (Court Appointed Special Advocate) volunteers in Texas, managed by these local programs, are assigned by judges to advocate for children in foster care. By coordinating efforts through Texas CASA, volunteers collectively serve more than half the children in state custody, ensuring those children have a consistent advocate focused on their safety and permanency.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.ScreenerQual_SW: Yes, recommended or preferred, but not required
policies.Def_OtherSpecify: Forcing or coercing a child to enter into a marriage
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Abuse includes emotional abuse, labor trafficking, physical abuse, sex trafficking, sexual abuse; Physical abuse includes substance use by parent, (specifically current use of a controlled substance, in a manner or to the extent that the use results in physical injury to a child and causing, expressly permitting, or encouraging a child to use a controlled substance); Emotional abuse include parental substance use (specifically the current use of a controlled substance, in a manner or to the extent that the use results in mental or emotional injury to a child)
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes abandonment, neglectful supervision, medical neglect, physical neglect, refusal to assume parental responsibility; Physical neglect includes the failure to provide a child with food, clothing, or shelter
policies.Exempt_OtherSpecify: Truancy; Runaway child; Children in need of supervision; Latch-key children; Harmful or violent children; Children with severe emotional disturbances
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.ConsentDecree_Specify: M.D. vs. Abbott (also known as M.D. vs. Perry)
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Arrange for joint investigation with law enforcement if Priority 1 and sexual abuse or physical abuse is alleged, or document why a joint investigation cannot occur; Visual examination of the child; Obtain demographic information from principals; Assess parent, other adults in home, and alleged perpetrator social history and information regarding substance use or abuse, mental health, domestic violence (in addition to criminal history and child welfare agency records); Contact parent who does not live in the home where the abuse/neglect is alleged to inform the parent about the investigation involving their child
policies.EquityStaff_OtherSpecify: (1) Manages the planning, development, and implementation of standards of services, statewide policies, and procedures for the agency designed to improve parity of outcomes for children, families and vulnerable elderly. Completes ongoing assignments and reports. Disseminates best practice guidelines. Provides professional guidance in the program area to regional managers, agency administrators, council and executive staff. (2) Performs oversight of program quality, coordination of internal and external advisory or work groups. Liaisons with regional disproportionality staff across the state to achieve departmental goals associated with diversity, equity and inclusion. (3) Establishes short-, mid-, and long-term goals and objectives; develops work plans and standards for achieving goals; and directs evaluation activities. Reports on the attainment of agency goals and levels of achievement. (4) Consults with various representatives, both internal and external to the agency, regarding collaborative activities associated with diversity, equity and inclusion, cultural humility, and cultural competency. Represents the Department of Family and Protective Services at meetings, hearings, trials, conferences and seminars or on boards, panels and committees. Testifies at hearings and legislative meetings.
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: For abandonment, the perpetrator is a parent, guardian, or managing or possessory conservator of the child
policies.ScreenInfo_VaryLocalSpecify: Screening for some reports follow regional protocols
policies.InvestQual_ExperienceSpecify: No experience required with bachelor's degree; 2 years of relevant work experience with associate's degree or 60 college credit hours; 1 year of relevant work experience with 90 college credit hours; Examples of relevant work experience in social, human, or protective services include paid or volunteer work within social service agencies or communities providing services to families or other at-risk populations
policies.InvestReq_OtherCases_Specify: Joint investigation is required for sexual and physical abuse; For visual examinations, the caseworker must have reasonable belief that the child may have physical signs of abuse or neglect; For obtaining demographic information, the caseworker must work with each principal to determine the principal's race or ethnicity and the language in which the principal communicates for all cases; Assessing parents, other adults, and alleged perpetrators social history, information regarding substance use or abuse, mental health, domestic violence required if alleged perpetrator is a parent or other adult; For contacting parent who does not live in the home, this is required if child's parents live in two separate homes
policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: 7-week training including Basic Skills Development (BSD) for new intake specialists and Advanced Skills Development (ASD) to all BSD graduates within 12 months of BSD
policies.CaseManagerQual_ExperienceSpec: No experience required with a bachelor's degree; 2 years of relevant work experience with associate's degree or 60 college credits; 1 year of relevant work experience with 90 college credit hours; Examples of relevant work experience in social, human, or protective services include paid or volunteer work within social service agencies or communities providing services to families or other at-risk populations
policies.NearFatalities_SpecificSpecify: Likelihood of death without medical intervention involving one or more of the following: 1) cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR), 2) medications to stabilize cardiac (heart) or respiratory (breathing) status, blood pressure, or critical electrolytes, 3) surgery to preserve brain function, to prevent blood loss, or to prevent infection
policies.AltResp_EligibilityMaltreatment: Only certain types of maltreatment are eligible
policies.ExtendedFosterCare_Age_OtherSpec: Generally up to age 21 (until 21st birthday); Up to age 22 (22nd birthday), if the young adult is regularly attending high school or a program leading toward a high school diploma or high school equivalence certificate
policies.InvestReq_HomeStudyCases_Specify: If there is an infant (under 12 months of age), the caseworker must observe the area where the infant sleeps for any unsafe sleep practices
policies.InvestReq_HomeVisitCases_Specify: If there is a principal child in the home who is 5 years old or younger; The allegations involve the condition of the home or other circumstances in the case make a home visit necessary to ensure child safety
policies.InvestReq_OtherChildrenCase_Spec: If the caseworker believes children have relevant information about the allegations or known danger to a child
